channel.description:
[b]Purpose:[/b] To teach you the basics in making GUI frames. How to make and use JButtons, JLabels, JTextFields, Action Listeners and more.

[b]Chapters[/b]
1 - How you should set out your GUI classes.
2 - Setting layouts & adding buttons and labels.
3 - ActionListener and showMessageDialog Method.
4 - Panels and how to use them.

Chapter 1

Ohaider and Welcome to my tut. Ok some of the basics that you really need when you making a GUI frame is importing swing, method main, public ClassName(), Setting layouts and Adding Labels/Buttons.

[code]
import javax.swing.*; 
//This imports everything we need for making JFrames.

public class ClassName extends JFrame {

private static ClassName frame;
//Doesn't need to be called frame but this is helpful later on. Rather than using 'this' for everything.

public static void main(String[] args) {
//The main method all runable java apps need this.

frame = new ClassName();
//Adds the componants in our class.

frame.setTitle("Title"); //The title in the quotation marks.
frame.setSize(25, 100); //Or can use pack();
/*
setPack would make it the size its needed to fit all your labels ect in.
without resizing them in anyway shape or form.
*/
frame.setDefaultCloseOperation(EXIT_ON_CLOSE); //Making it close properly
frame.setVisible(true); //Making it visible to the user
//We use frame. because thats what were called our frame.
}

public ClassName() { //This is where we add all our componants.

setLayout(new SOMETHINGLayout()); // Setting layout will explain layout. SOMETHING = The layout.

Jlabel label = new JLabel("String"); //String = The lablel text
JButton button = new JButton("String"); //String = The button text

add(label);
add(button); //Adding our button and label companants.
}[/code]

Thats the basic set out with the basics to it now I can tell you how to use Labels and setting the layout of you GUI. Firstly I'll tell you all the layouts you can use.

[code]setLayout(new GridLayout(#, #));[/code]
Makes a new layout that places your objects in each block of the grid and is the size of # x # blocks. They will be streched/shrunk if you have the setsize.

[code]setLayout(new FlowLayout());[/code]
A more basic layout which just fits as much as it can on one line then makes another link. It also centres the items on each line.

[code]setLayout(new BorderLayout());[/code]
Makes 5 panels so to say. North, East, West, South and Center (Must spell Centre American way). and you can add things to each panel.

when adding Labels ect. to BorderLayout use following usage:
[code]	add(OBJECTNAME, BorderLayout.NORTH); //Orientation words must be in full caps.[/code]

So, at the top just under 
[code]public ClassName() {[/code]
add any layout.

with any layout except Border you can just use the normal add() method. The usage is simply:
[code]	add(OBJECTNAME);[/code]

They will then go left to right accordingly to what order the adds are in in the public ClassName().

Declaring JLabels and Buttons

[code]JButton BUTTONNAME = new JButton("Button Text");
JLabel LABELNAME = new JLabel("Button Text");[/code]

Chapter 3

The ActionListener class must be implemented and you must import java.awt.event.*;. The action listener listens for buttons being pressed in the GUI environment. The method below must be used to listen for button pressing. it must have actionEvent, it does not have to be e but e is the default and is recomended. I strongly recomend making a string = e.getActionCommand you can make it short making it easier to construct if statements for your buttons.

[code]    public void actionPerformed(ActionEvent e) { //e = Default
        String a = e.getActionCommand(); //Making it easier to make if statements
        JOptionPane.showMessageDialog(frame, "You pressed button " + click + "!"); //A message dialog.
    }
}[/code]

There is no if statements in that method hence that same action happening for all the buttons pressed in the application. If you wanted an if statement in this method you'd simply go:
[code]if(a.equals("STRING IN THE BUTTON") {[/code] 
then you could specify different actions for different buttons.

JOptionPane.showMessageDialog makes a seperate frame appear with the message in the string. If you declared your class globally as frame it is must easier like i have recomended if you have not done that "frame" becomes "this" then followed buy your string that will appear.

Chapter 4

Panels are very useful in that they are the closest thing to customization in your simple GUI. Not using netbeans or anything like that. what panels do is allow you to set different layouts within your layout.

So lets say we firstly set a borderlayout to the whole GUI. So 
[code]setLayout(new BorderLayout());[/code]

Lets say I wanted to put 6 Buttons in the brid panel in a grid and 4 in the south in a grid panel. We would declare 2 panels. So for example:
[code]	JPanel panel = new JPanel();
	panel.setLayout(new GridLayout(2, 3));

	JPanel panel2 = new JPanel();
	panel2.setLayout(new GridLayout(2, 2));[/code]

We'd then want to add our two panels.
[code]	add(panel1, BorderLayout.NORTH);
	add(panel2, BorderLayout.CENTER);[/code]

So we can specify where we want our panels now by doing this.

So we now want to add our buttons to the 2 panels. So we first need to make all our buttons.
[code]	JButton button1 = new JButton("Text");
	JButton button2 = new JButton("Text");
	JButton button3 = new JButton("Text");
	JButton button4 = new JButton("Text");
	JButton button5 = new JButton("Text");
	JButton button6 = new JButton("Text");
	JButton button7 = new JButton("Text");
	JButton button8 = new JButton("Text");
	JButton button9 = new JButton("Text");
	JButton button10 = new JButton("Text");[/code]

Now when adding our Buttons to the panel we use the add method differently we use as:
[code]PANELNAME.add(OBJNAME);[/code]

So lets add them for our example.
[code]
panel1.add(button1);
panel1.add(button2);
panel1.add(button3);
panel1.add(button4);
panel1.add(button5);
panel1.add(button6);

panel2.add(button7);
panel2.add(button8);
panel2.add(button9);
panel2.add(button10);
[/code]

That will now make a frame with 6 buttons at the top and 4 buttons at the bottom all in a grid and seperate. And that concludes chapter 4.

